name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I was inspired by the energy at NFT NYC last week, and it got me thinking about my time as an entrepreneur during the early web2 era. The ideas here overlap with the tweet thread I posted yesterday, with added context and details from my personal experiences. üëá

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: If we are headed for an economic downturn, there are some tactical lessons from the 2008 era, namely preserving capital and staying focused on your long-term vision. But the main lesson is to ignore the noise and stay squarely focused on the product cycle.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I believe crypto and web3 will be at the center of the next cycle. We‚Äôve reach a critical mass of technology, talent, and community knowledge. In the almost 10 years I‚Äôve been involved in the space, the energy and creativity has never been higher.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The tech industry is very different today than it was in 2008. A handful of tech incumbents dominate the internet, exerting vast economic and cultural influence. Entrenched interests aggressively respond to new movements that might someday threaten them.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For example, as the iPhone improved, better apps were possible. Better apps helped drive iPhone sales, giving Apple more money to invest, enabling even better apps, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The growth phase starts when the right mix of technology, talent, and community knowledge comes together. It is driven by a reinforcing feedback loop between infrastructure and applications.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For example, there were credible attempts to create smartphones as early as 1990. Smartphones continued to advance for the next 15 years, but it wasn‚Äôt until after the iPhone launched that they transitioned from the incubation to the growth phase.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: They begin with an incubation phase in which enthusiasts explore ideas and build products that are mostly used by other enthusiasts.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Product cycles follow their own internal logic and tend to be more predictable than financial cycles.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The next row shows the years that iconic startups or products were created. The timing is mostly dictated by product cycles, which are shown in the bottom row.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The key idea is that product and financial cycles evolve mostly independently. The top of the chart shows the Nasdaq index as a rough proxy for financial sentiment. Financial sentiment fluctuates unpredictably and sometimes wildly.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I made the chart below to summarize how I've come to think about product and financial cycles. https://t.co/JBFg4cHpBb

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Independent product design spaces are multiplicative: even if social, cloud, and mobile each improved linearly, the combination could improve exponentially.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In retrospect, that era was propelled by a combination of three powerful trends: social media, cloud computing, and the rise of smartphones.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Most of today‚Äôs top mobile apps were created by companies founded between 2009 and 2011, including Uber, Venmo, Snap, and Instagram.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: But from a startup perspective, 2008 and the following 3 years turned out to be a golden age. Apple released the iPhone in 2007 and the app store in 2008. By 2009 talented founders were pouring in.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There‚Äôs a lot of talk lately about the possibility of a prolonged financial downturn, reminiscent of 2008. 2008 was a difficult time for many people.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
web3 takes us back to the internet‚Äôs original vision: a decentralized network governed by open protocols, where power and money flow to the edges instead of centralized intermediaries.

I wrote more about why web3 matters here: https://t.co/nkxHsBiiqC

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
> Ethos

Finally, and most importantly, is the web3 ethos.

The internet has become increasingly dominated by a handful of incumbent tech companies.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
In web3, promises to developers are baked into the system via immutable, open source code (‚Äúcan‚Äôt be evil‚Äù). 

This means developers can count on credible neutrality, the way they could in web1. 

This will lead to a new wave of widespread, permissionless innovation.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Web2 tried to make developer commitments via  promises (‚Äúdon‚Äôt be evil‚Äù). 

This didn‚Äôt work, as we‚Äôve seen over the years. Web2 platforms routinely deprecate APIs and change terms of service with little regard for third-party developers.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Developers want to know they are building on a credibly neutral platform where the rules won‚Äôt change. 

Web1 protocols like HTTP and SMTP did this very well, leading to an explosion of innovation.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web3 projects can tap into a vastly larger talent pool by creating and nurturing a developer ecosystem.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
This is because smart people with relevant expertise are everywhere. 

As Bill Joy famously said: ‚Äúno matter who you are, most of the smartest people work for someone else.‚Äù

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
> Ecosystem 

The vast majority of software running in the world is open source, created by communities of developers.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Instead of building your service on top of incumbent platforms or using paid advertising, web3 lets you build it via the enthusiasm of users. 

This dramatically lowers the cost of customer acquisition, and lets you build much higher-quality communities.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Second, in web3 tokens are self-marketing. When someone genuinely owns something and feels skin in the game, they want to evangelize it.
https://t.co/XDPdnGUti6

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
A great example of this is Helium, which has used token incentives to build a nationwide grassroots telecom service to take on the telecom incumbents. 
https://t.co/8NnS13V3z1

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
First, web3 enables projects to offer token incentives to users in the early phase when the native network effects are weak.

This helps overcome the bootstrap problem that has defeated so many promising early-stage startups in the past. https://t.co/TmudHfTRhd

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
> Marketing

Web3 unlocks powerful new marketing techniques.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Overall NFT sales volumes have been averaging billions of dollars a month. 

At current trends, web3 creator payouts will soon surpass web2 creator payouts.
https://t.co/o6RSitKDbD

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
For example, social networks like Instagram and Twitter don‚Äôt share any revenue with the creators who made them popular.

In web3, creators can go direct to their audiences by selling things like NFTs, earning 90% or more of the revenue they generate. 

https://t.co/ToIK4LX7HB

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This provides an opportunity for startups to attract and foster communities by providing superior economics to creators, developers, and other network participants.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
That said, we are still early in the exploration of the DAO design space. 

There will likely be opportunities to apply DAOs to novel areas and create breakthrough products.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In the past year, thousands of DAOs have been created across a broad range of categories including financial services, investing, content creation, games, social clubs, and more.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: DAOs are novel web3 constructs that supercharge online communities by providing more sophisticated coordination methods and control over internet-native financial resources.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
> Product

Wikipedia is simply a better encyclopedia than traditional encyclopedias because it harnesses the knowledge and creativity of its community.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Instead of hoping that application/network designers do the right thing (‚Äúdon‚Äôt be evil‚Äù), web3 creates new systems where the rules are enforced by code (‚Äúcan‚Äôt be evil‚Äù) and the incentives of the network and the network participants are fully aligned.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This example illustrates a very nice property of web3: the incentives of the network/application are fully aligned with the incentives of the network participants (users, developers, creators, etc).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
The key is that by ascribing value to the users' data and assets, you create an incentive for users to join and grow your network. 

Moreover, you can help guide the kind of community you  develop by deciding which networks to interoperate with first.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There is no reason the fungible tokens have to behave the same way in the smaller game as in the bigger game. There is also no reason the NFTs have to have the same purpose, appearance, or functionality.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For example, let‚Äôs say you are a startup web3 game and admire that fan base that a larger web3 game has built. An effective way to attract their community is to accept their tokens ‚Äì fungibles and NFTs ‚Äì into your network.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This is where it gets interesting. The smaller network not only has an incentive to interoperate but can use interoperability as a core growth mechanic.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Again, by simple application of Metcalf‚Äôs Law, the larger network has an incentive to block interoperability, but in web3 they can't do this.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
This is a bad outcome for network participants: users have a worse experiences and get locked-in to applications.  

Developers and creators have a harder time getting started and growing their audiences, and also risk lock-in.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Play this logic out over many years and we end up with the internet we have today, where almost no applications/networks interoperate (beyond the networks that carried over from web1, the web and email).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: As a result, larger web2 networks almost always decide not to interoperate, and because they fully control all the user data, this is easy for them to do.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: By a simple application of Metcalf‚Äôs Law, when two networks compete, the incentive for the smaller network is to want to interoperate, while the incentive for the larger network is to not want to interoperate.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In web2, applications completely control user data, so each application gets to decide unilaterally whether to interoperate with other applications.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
One thing that trips people up when migrating from web2 to web3 is that the ‚Äúlaws of physics‚Äù in web3 can be very different that in web2.

A good example is the incentives around applications deciding whether to interoperate with one another.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Side note: DNS is the unsung hero of web1. A mapping between network layer (domain name) and physical layer (IP), controlled fully by users, enabling them to keep centralized services in check with a credible ability to exit.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: web3 provides a new way to build networks that combines the publicly-owned network effects of web1 with the advanced functionality of web2. https://t.co/nkxHsBzTPc

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The good news is we are still early in the development of the internet and there will likely be many new networks built in the coming decades.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web2 is dominated by incumbents who spend vast sums of money extracting data and money from the networks they control. There is a serious risk the internet turns out like, say, broadcast TV with a few dominant corporate-owned services, and no room for startups and new ideas.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: A public park in a city attracts passersby which in turn helps nearby restaurants and other businesses. In the same way, publicly-owned networks unlock entrepreneurship and opportunity that wouldn‚Äôt otherwise exist.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Entrepreneurs and investors in the 90s knew they could freely build and invest without fear that the network would change their economics or deprecate their access, as happens regularly with privately-owned networks.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There will be centralized services in web3. Indeed, as we saw in web1, publicly-owned networks unlock a massive wave of innovation and entrepreneurship around them.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
There are a variety of centralized services that let you access this network including OpenSea, Zora, LooksRare, etc. 

But the network effect doesn‚Äôt accrue to these service, as I explain here https://t.co/HRzMVYQZYk

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For example, Ethereum NFTs can be viewed as a network where users and NFTs interoperate and form connections. This network is built on the Ethereum blockchain. Users have full control of their data.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Blockchains provide a powerful new way to build networks where the network effects accrue as public goods, as they did in web1.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Network effects are what enable the corporate-owned networks like Facebook and Twitter to accrue dominant positions and command very high take rates (web2 take rates range from 30%-100%).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The killer app of the internet is networks. The web and email are networks. Social apps like Instagram and Twitter are networks. Marketplaces like Uber and Airbnb are networks.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
But I can leave my web hosting provider and still keep my inbound links, search rankings, etc by switching my DNS record. 

That‚Äôs because in web1 the network effects accrued as a public resource thanks to open protocols like HTTP and SMTP and community-owned services like DNS.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Network effects are the main source of user and developer lock-in. If I try to leave Twitter, I lose the followers I built up over the years. That‚Äôs because in web2 the network effects accrued to private companies like Twitter.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There will be centralized services in web3 just as there were in web1. The key question in web3 is whether the network effects accrue as private goods (as they did in web2) or public goods (as they did in web1).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This criticism is based on a mistaken understanding of what web3 advocates mean by decentralization. I‚Äôll try to explain.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: A recent criticism of web3 is that it isn‚Äôt actually decentralized, because there are centralized services in the mix, such as NFT marketplaces like OpenSea, and data availability services like Alchemy. üßµ

web2's take rate is web3's opportunity https://t.co/ToIK4MeIz9

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
This is why web3 take rates are dramatically lower than web2 take rates. OpenSea, for example, charges 2.5% on transactions. 

Compare this to web2 take rates. FB, Twitter, & Instagram take 100% of revenue. YouTube takes 45% of revenue. Apple and Google app stores take 30%.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: web3 works like web1 did. There will be centralized services built in web3 ‚Äî and many will be quite useful ‚Äî but their economic power and overall control will be limited by the lower switching costs due to data portability.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Compare this to web2. Many people spend years building an audience on web2 services, but if those services decide to reduce your organic reach or otherwise misbehave it's basically impossible to switch.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: And I can make this switch without losing the audience I‚Äôve built up over time via inbound links, SEO, email subscribers, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This is similar to how web1 worked. For example, I host https://t.co/0ht41THWGJ at a web hosting provider. If the host starts misbehaving, I can easily move my data to another host and switch my DNS records so https://t.co/0ht41THWGJ points there.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Why is data portability important? 

It means that users can easily switch services if those services start charging too much, inserting ads and algorithmic feeds, throttling their traffic, or mistreating them in other ways.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Also, although short term it‚Äôs frustrating, long term it‚Äôs a massively positive signal that the main criticisms of NFTs is based on false premises. Eventually the truth will propagate out.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
The internet is a giant meme-propagation machine. 

NFTs work with the internet instead of fighting it, increasing the abundance of creative works while also allowing creators to get properly paid for their work.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
The most forward-thinking NFT projects make the content itself public domain. 

The more you copy and share the content, the more popular the project becomes, increasing the likelihood of the NFTs becoming valuable.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
This concept of ownership independent of copyright is widely understood in the offline world. 

There can be many copies of a work of art or other cultural artifact. 

As depictions of the original are more widely shared, owning the original becomes more valuable.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: NFTs add a new layer of value ‚Äî digital ownership ‚Äî that didn‚Äôt exist in a credible way before NFTs.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Many critics of NFTs claim the opposite ‚Äî that NFTs restrict access to creative content. 

This is not a critique of NFTs. This is a critique of a fictional caricature of NFTs dreamt up by critics.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: NFTs make art, music, writing, games, and other creative content more abundant, not more scarce.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
NFTs are completely independent from copyright.

You can pick any copyright you want for an NFT.

A popular (and I think best choice) is CC0=public domain.

Letting creators monetize while removing copyright does the *opposite* of imposing scarcity‚Äîit increases sharing/abundance.

tweet: This year we‚Äôve seen an explosion of innovation around NFTs. This will likely continue for many years as it‚Äôs still extremely early in the evolution of web3.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
This could be something simple like your viewing preferences or much more advanced things like your entire social graph. 

This would allow you to switch from one service to another seamlessly ‚Äì and have full control of your own data, a key part of the web3 vision.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: ‚ñ† Web2 databases. Using cryptographic methods and decentralized data stores, you can extend NFTs to anything stored in a centralized web2 database today.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Today this means a better way to login (https://t.co/1KYGYNcTbc) & identify yourself in an interoperable way using systems like ENS. 

Later, you might store and selectively reveal other aspects of your identity using NFTs for things like records, credentials, and reputation.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Contrary to what you might think from reading the news, blockchains like Bitcoin and Ethereum have never been hacked. 

In web3, users are in charge: there is no centralized database to hack or sell.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: ‚ñ† Identity. The web2 way of handling personal information has failed. Your sensitive personal information has been hacked many times. Handling passwords is a mess. Long privacy policies and terms of service get changed on a whim.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For example, many high-end collectors of physical goods keep their collections in a vault. You could create a digital token representing them, letting them be showcased and traded digitally, reducing friction and intermediaries, and expanding the UX possibilities.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: ‚ñ† Redeemables. Unisocks was a whimsical pioneer of the model where a token could be redeemed for a physical good. This mechanism can be applied to lots of offline goods.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Pioneering games like Axie Infinity and Top Shot kicked off a wave of new web3 game development. Many of these projects should launch next year.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: NFTs allow users to genuinely own the objects, flipping the polarity: games build around user-owned objects instead of users having to depend on the game.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: As we‚Äôve seen again and again in the history of tech, interoperability and composability dramatically accelerate innovation. https://t.co/VG5EQrie72

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: ‚ñ† Game objects. Web2 gamers spend about $40B/year on virtual goods. But users don‚Äôt really own those objects, the company does. And the objects cannot interoperate and compose across games.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
‚ñ† Access. NFTs make tickets low friction and widely interoperable. 

You can use them to replace traditional tickets, lowering friction and making them more interoperable. 

A more native use case is digital access, like a private discord server or video lessons.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
3. Generational desire for new frontiers

A lot of what I do in my job is talk to people moving into web3, either as founders or as employees in companies I work with. Many are coming from big tech companies.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Framed this way, we are nowhere near the logical endpoint of the internet's evolution.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Those applications can have a profound impact on how power and money is distributed across the internet. 

Thinking about computing improvements along economic and political vectors is very foreign to the traditional tech mindset.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Blockchains offer to improve computers along different vectors. Specifically, they allow computers to make credible commitments that in turn unlock new classes of applications. https://t.co/7SB4843Wam

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: People with this mindset look at a blockchain and see a slow database. (And while blockchains performance is improving rapidly, running a consensus mechanism will always have some performance overhead.)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The assumption is that the only vectors of improvement that matter are the ones the tech industry has traditionally focused on: greater data availability, better computing performance, smaller devices, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
2. New vectors of computing improvement 

Ben argued that one reason the software industry is mature is that it has reached its logical endpoint. https://t.co/br8V5Fhv9f

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Computers connected to the internet are, by and large, free to run whatever software their owners choose. Whatever can be dreamt up, with the right set of incentives, can quickly propagate across the internet.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Moreover, the internet was specifically designed to embrace this plasticity. 

The internet is the ultimate software-based network, consisting of a relatively simple core layer connecting billions of fully programmable computers at the edge.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: But it‚Äôs a mistake to analogize software to hardware. Software has a much richer design space ‚Äî closer in the breadth of possibilities to creative activities like fiction writing than traditional engineering. https://t.co/Fp0Jc7rmY3

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
1. Plasticity of software and the internet. 

The core of most of these arguments are analogies to past industries. Ben cites the auto industry. Other writers cite past information networks like broadcast TV and radio.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I believe there are at least 3 major reasons why this view is wrong: plasticity of software and the internet, new vectors of computing improvement, and generational desire for new frontiers. I'll explain these below.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In my experience, this view is tacitly held by most of the establishment: institutional investors, tech execs, policymakers, media, etc. It affects valuations, corporate behavior, media coverage, and policy making.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Ben Thompson provides an excellent articulation of this view (as he often does) https://t.co/XT4UfVAJ5j https://t.co/hw1ayVrh8w

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There is a widespread view that the internet and software industry is now mature, that the historical pattern of disruptive revolutions every 10-15 years is now over. üßµ

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Now of course what makes these strategic questions more art than science is you need to consider not just the loop today but in the near- and long-term future.

Predicting this is a complex and fascinating mix of technology, markets, psychology, culture, and strategy.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Amazon‚Äôs strength is its logistics network. Google and Apple are strongest at the device, OS and app layer. Facebook‚Äôs strategic position is the weakest but is making bold bets on next-gen devices. All four are trying to either commoditize or own adjacent layers.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Looking at this chart, it should be clear why most of the big tech companies have efforts in almost all positions in the loop.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: It‚Äôs much better to have complements be open source and free vs controlled by a competitor. This is why, for example, the biggest contributor to Linux is Intel.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: A big reason big tech companies invest in open source software is to ‚Äúcommoditize the complement‚Äù (see this classic Joel Spolsky post on the topic https://t.co/LCAeDyx57O).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: New technologies come along (which often look toy-like and unthreatening at first) that create entirely new tracks that render the previous tracks obsolete.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Think of the economic loop pictured above as a model train track. Positions in front of you can redirect traffic around you. Positions after you can build new tracks that bypass you.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Many fiercest battles in the history of the internet have been between complements, going back to Microsoft vs Netscape.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Hamburgers and hotdogs are substitutes. You generally choose one or the other. Examples in tech: AT&T vs Verizon, iPhone vs Android phone.

Hotdogs and hotdog buns are complements. Examples in tech: an internet provider and a search engine, a browser and a social network.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Note on complements: people usually think of substitutes when they think about competition, but with internet businesses complements are often a bigger threat & opportunity.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Suppose you are Google and a user clicks on an ad which leads to a $1 purchase. The strategic question is how Google positions itself to get the most of that $1 vs the complements and substitutes in this chart, now and in the future.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Consider the path of a typical internet session, from the user to some revenue-generating action, and then (in some cases) back again to the user 

(I wrote more about this here https://t.co/4RhUYRtmab) https://t.co/RzrOz0aqu1

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I‚Äôll explain by looking at the current internet landscape and the strategic position of Google, Facebook, Amazon, and Apple. (I‚Äôll adapt this to web3 in a future thread.)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Something I find useful is mapping out the typical economic loop from start to finish, and then considering the startup‚Äôs position within that loop.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Let‚Äôs say you run a startup that has a successful product, and you are now considering what product you should build or acquire next. üßµ

Also, self-marketing networks are a very powerful force. 

In the good case, this force is paired with a genuinely useful network.

That has not always been the case, leading to memecoins and such.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This is also why the token distribution mechanics are so important. The key is fostering a genuine community‚Äî and distributing ownership to the people who do the hard work of actually building the network.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Removing advertising, and relying on community-led R&D, transforms the economics of internet services. This enables web3 services to have zero or very low take rates. https://t.co/ToIK4MeIz9

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: (This couldn‚Äôt have happened without social media. In the pre-social media days, it was vastly harder to do bottoms-up evangelizing. In this way, web2 enables web3.)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Bitcoin is the ultimate case study of this: a trillion-dollar network that was built through community-led evangelism and R&D.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Tokens are self-marketing. When someone genuinely owns something and feels skin in the game, they want to evangelize it.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This means you no longer need advertising.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Instead of the value and control accruing to a company at the center, it gets distributed out to the edges, to the people who actually build the network.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web3 takes a different approach by letting users and builders participate in the growth of networks as genuine owners. https://t.co/nkxHsBiiqC

tweet: When you build a business on advertising, the theory is that if you retain enough customers, the long-term economics will work out and you‚Äôll eventually be profitable.

tweet: Web2 is built on advertising. Big companies like Facebook and Google make most of their money on advertising, and many web2 startups build their customer base using advertising.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Computing movements are positive-sum games. There can be many winners at both the infrastructure and application layer. 

It's important to run a variety of experiments ‚Äî and stay focused on the bigger goal of bringing blockchains and web3 mainstream.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: It's also important to have many blockchain infrastructure projects because when exponential growth kicks in, we will likely have a consistent shortage of high-quality infrastructure.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
For example it‚Äôs plausible to imagine a world where frequent-use, low-value transactions happen on blockchains that trade security for performance.

Assets that increase in value can then be moved to other blockchains that prioritize security over performance.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Some of the designs will fail. Others will make fundamental trade offs.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The more blockchain infrastructure projects, the better. For one things, it's important to fully explore the design space, including different approaches to scaling, security, governance, developer and user experience, etc.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Many of the apps that will drive this growth probably haven‚Äôt even been launched yet. It‚Äôs possible they haven‚Äôt even been imagined yet.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Today, Ethereum has roughly 10M monthly users, which is roughly 0.2% of all internet users. Over the 2020s, usage will hopefully grow significantly both in terms of number of users and in terms of the number and frequency of transactions per user.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
It's very likely that similar to other important computing resources of the past, demand for blockchains will consistently outpace supply. 

This is already true for Ethereum itself, and will likely also be the case for L2s, side chains, and other L1s.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Now let's talk about blockchains. Programmable blockchains are computers: you can write (near) Turing-complete code for them, store information in them, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This pattern happens over and over, and is one of the main reasons computers have become ubiquitous and so important in our lives.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: As GPUs got better, game developers invested in higher fidelity graphics and experiences, which grew the video games market, giving GPU makers more money to reinvest in chips, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In the 2000s, when broadband penetration reached minimally viable levels, entrepreneurs created video-sharing sites like YouTube, which spurred broadband demand even more, making video steaming work even better, in a reinforcing loop.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Consider a modern smartphone. The phone itself is much better than a decade ago, and so are the apps. The apps drove the popularity of the phones which gave manufacturers more money to reinvest. Improved phones increased the app design space, and the cycle repeated.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The core dynamic of computing movements is a mutually reinforcing feedback loop between applications and infrastructure.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For every important computing resource in history demand has outpaced supply. This includes CPUs, GPUs, memory, storage, and both wired and wireless bandwidth.

tweet: The myth of "ETH killers" ‚Äî why demand for blockchains will always outpace supply üßµ

There are various exponential forces in the world to look out for, as they can be indicators of rapid future growth. 

In hardware, the most powerful exponential force is Moore‚Äôs Law. In finance, it's compounding interest. In software, it's composability.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: One of the most exciting aspects of web3 is the composability of protocols and tokens. We see this is in DeFi when protocols build on top of each other the way composite protocols like Yearn or Element do.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Open source began as a fringe political movement in the 80s and remained mostly a curiosity through the 90s, but started growing exponentially in the 2000s and after. 

Why? Because open source unlocked the power composability.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: A very high percentage of the software in the world is open source. Most datacenter software is open source, mobile phones OSs make heavy use of open source, most next-gen devices like self-driving cars, drones, and embedded computers run mostly open source software.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 3 extends this power beyond software to  services, making it possible to build an open internet that doesn't compromise on features or user experience.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The power of open source software is, as @naval says, that the world only has to solve each problem once https://t.co/bCOsbp9ywP

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This will hopefully unlock a new wave of innovation. Open services support composability‚Äî the ability to remix open services the way you can currently remix open source software.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: We‚Äôre about to see a wave of new consumer apps including social networks that take advantage of this.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Combined with the right front-end clients, open services can now match the advanced functionality and streamlined onboarding of centralized services.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This means that in Web 3 you can now build advanced protocols that are open like RSS but also store things like usernames, social graphs, and posts in a credibly neutral way.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: (For those who didn‚Äôt realize that modern blockchains are fully developed, near Turing-complete computers, there are in-depth materials on the topic here https://t.co/xTWVS6cpqw

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In Web 3, almost all projects choose to have the code run fully autonomously (controlled by no one) or controlled by a community.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: When you deploy code to Ethereum, the code runs autonomously and perpetually. The author of the code can choose to have the code (and the data it operates on) controlled by a community, a person, or no one at all.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Today, we have programmable blockchains like Ethereum. Programmable blockchains are virtual computers that run code and keep state.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: (I wrote more about this topic back in 2017 here https://t.co/vauyfPYkyB) https://t.co/pNjgeF2QYm

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
So then services like Twitter came along that adopted the best features of open protocols but made it extremely easy to onboard and use. 

The catch: you were using their database and code, handing full control over to a centralized organization.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Anyone who builds consumer software will tell you that an onboarding experience that requires more than a few, simple steps is ngmi.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: But these protocols relied on outside parties to store data. For users who wanted to publish a social feed while controlling their data, this usually meant registering a domain name and signing up for a hosting provider.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
Why did closed, proprietary services win out?

We had the building blocks for open social networks back in 2007, including RSS and lesser known, related protocols.

name: cdixon.eth

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 3 allows the users and builders who create networks to own a meaningful piece of them, while also unlocking powerful new tools for entrepreneurs.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: I‚Äôve worked in Web 3 and crypto since 2013 and have never worked with a project that spent meaningful money on sales and marketing. You don‚Äôt need to spend money on marketing when users are genuine owners, love what they do, and love telling other people about it.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Token incentives are effective, but also far fairer than the centralized Web 2 model. Shouldn‚Äôt the people who helped build a network get to own a meaningful piece of it?

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Another network that‚Äôs been bootstrapped with token incentives is Arweave, a decentralized storage network. The Arweave network has grown roughly 12x in the last year. Here‚Äôs the growth over the last 2 years. (Full network explorer here https://t.co/zjaESjrZyV) https://t.co/F9lWhjaPZG

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Helium uses the power of token incentives to bootstrap the supply side. It‚Äôs worked well so far. The network has over 200,000 nodes worldwide. Here‚Äôs a coverage map of the US and another zoomed into the Bay Area. (Here‚Äôs the full network explorer https://t.co/JtDRUcRABe) https://t.co/Mx9kWP6aKE

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The core problem is how do you get enough equipment installed to get broad coverage while also building out the demand side. It‚Äôs a classic chicken-and-egg problem.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: (Btw the idea of a grassroots, bottoms-up telecom to take on the entrenched incumbents is a perennial techie fantasy, and there have been many noble attempts to build it including early Fon and early Meraki/Roofnet. Web 3 might finally make it happen.)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Let‚Äôs look at some examples. Helium is trying to create a grassroots competitor to big telecom companies by incentivizing individuals to install networking equipment in their home.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There are lots of intricacies about how to design the token schedule and keep out spammers and scammers, which I won‚Äôt go into here but is a very interesting topic.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Over time, as the network effect and native utility grows, the token incentives taper off and eventually go to zero, and the world is left with a new, scaled network.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: (This chart comes from a longer blog post I wrote on the topic back in 2017: https://t.co/vauyfPYkyB)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The basic idea is: early on during the bootstrapping phase when network effects haven‚Äôt kicked in, provide users with financial utility via token rewards to make up for the lack of native utility. https://t.co/RG6mPbRbrt

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 3 introduces a powerful new tool for bootstrapping networks: token incentives.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Because bootstrapping networks is so hard, it‚Äôs likely that there are many networks that should exist‚Äîthat would improve our collective well-being‚Äî but don‚Äôt because no one has figured out how to bootstrap them.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: In the Web 2 era, overcoming the bootstrapping problem meant heroic entrepreneurial efforts, plus in many cases spending lots of money on sales and marketing.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Networks get more valuable with more participants, which is great when they are at scale, but cuts the other way when starting out. This is the bootstrapping problem.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The killer app of the internet is networks. The web and email are networks. Social apps like Instagram and Twitter are networks. Marketplaces like Uber and Airbnb are networks.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: The Web 3 playbook: using token incentives to bootstrap new networks. üßµ

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 3 offers a new way that combines the best aspects of the previous eras. It‚Äôs very early in this movement and a great time to get involved.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Before Web 3, users and builders had to choose between the limited functionality of Web 1 or the corporate, centralized model of Web 2.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: This fixes the core problem of centralized networks, where the value is accumulated by one company, and the company ends up fighting its own users and partners.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Tokens align network participants to work together toward a common goal ‚Äî the growth of the network and the appreciation of the token.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: You can also earn tokens through creative and entrepreneurial activities. For example, people are earning roughly $100M worth of ETH per day selling NFTs.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Uniswap famously retroactively airdropped 15% of its governance tokens to early users of the protocol. Community grants like this have become common in Web 3 as a way to build goodwill and incentivize adoption.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: There are many ways for users to acquire fungible and non-fungible tokens. You can buy them, but there are also ways to earn them.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Ethereum is powered by a fungible token, ETH, which is used to incentivize the physical computers that underlie the system. ETH is also the system‚Äôs native currency for transactions, like NFT purchases.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Blockchains are special computers that anyone can access but no one owns.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: NFTs exist on top of blockchains like Ethereum. Ethereum is a decentralized global computer that is owned and operated by its users.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: NFTs give users the ability to own objects, which can be art, photos, code, music, text, game objects, credentials, governance rights, access passes, and whatever else people dream up next.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Tokens give users property rights: the ability to own a piece of the internet.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Now let‚Äôs talk about Web 3. In Web 3, ownership and control is decentralized. Users and builders can own pieces of internet services by owning tokens, both non-fungible (NFTs) and fungible.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: For 3rd parties, the transition from cooperation to competition feels like a bait-and-switch. Over time, the best entrepreneurs, developers, and investors have learned to not build on top of centralized platforms. This has stifled innovation.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Famous examples of this are Microsoft vs. Netscape, Google vs. Yelp, Facebook vs. Zynga,  Twitter vs. its 3rd-party clients, and Epic vs Apple.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: When they hit the top of the S-curve, their relationships with network participants change from positive-sum to zero-sum. To continue growing requires extracting data from users and competing with (former) partners.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: They do this to strengthen their network effect. As platforms move up the adoption S-curve, their power over users and 3rd parties steadily grows. https://t.co/KwOCGl5Hje

name: cdixon.eth

Why does Web 3 matter?

First, let‚Äôs look at the problems with centralized platforms. (I wrote more about this back in 2018 here https://t.co/KvyyhalCos)

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 3 is the internet owned by the builders and users, orchestrated with tokens.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: We are now at the beginning of the Web 3 era, which combines the decentralized, community-governed ethos of Web 1 with the advanced, modern functionality of Web 2.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 2 (roughly 2005-2020) was about siloed, centralized services run by corporations. Most of the value accrued to a handful of companies like Google, Apple, Amazon, and Facebook.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: Web 1 (roughly 1990-2005) was about open protocols that were decentralized and community-governed. Most of the value accrued to the edges of the network ‚Äî users and builders.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 17/ Those are great initial applications, and will likely remain very important, but tokens are better thought of as a new digital primitive, analogous to the website‚Äî the atomic unit around which a new era of the internet is organized.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 16/ There is nothing intrinsic about fungible tokens that needs to be related to money and finance, and nothing intrinsic about NFTs that needs to be related to art and collectibles.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 15/ Composable NFT games like Loot incentivize the community to build an entire world around a single set of NFTs‚Äî  an activity that would be impossible without the ownership and portability that Web 3 enables.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 14/ For example, building on mechanism designs pioneered by DeFi entrepreneurs, a new wave of DAOs are exploring ways for groups to come together, pool resources, build things, and self-govern.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 13/ We are still very much in the skeuomorphic era of Web 3, but are starting to see a new wave of native applications that have no prior analogue and simply couldn‚Äôt have existed before.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 12/ Users can now have a persistent inventory of objects in their wallet that they take from one app to another. If their objects increase in value, the user gets the upside. This is a big change from Web 2 where the upside was mostly captured by tech companies.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ Web 2 left out digital property rights. When you use a site (or app), it would only let you borrow or rent things. Imagine if in the real world you had to buy everything from scratch every time you went to a new place. That‚Äôs Web 2.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ Tokens give users property rights: the ability to own a piece of the internet.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ Tokens‚Äîfungibles and NFTs‚Äî are better thought of as new digital primitives, similar in flexibility and generality to past digital primitives like the website.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ A lot of today‚Äôs NFTs are adaptations from the offline world of art and collectibles. This leads people to think that NFTs are limited to those domains, in the same way people once thought the web was limited to brochures and magazines.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ Popular skeuomorphic Web 3 ideas include offline ticketing, supply chain management, and record keeping for offline assets. These may be good ideas, just as read-only websites were a good idea, but they only scratch the surface of what Web 3 can be.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ This pattern is repeating itself with crypto/Web 3. There are some great native Web 3 products, but overall we are still in the skeuomorphic era. Many Web 3 products are adaptations from older domains.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ It took about a decade for technologists to start seriously exploring the idea that websites could be read/write, where users generate the content. This led to the growth of web native categories like social networking, crowdfunding, and social productivity apps.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ In the skeuomorphic era, the design thinking is largely adapted from older domains. For example, the early web was mostly digital adaptations of pre-internet activities like letter writing and mail-order shopping. Websites back then were mostly read only.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 2/ Major computing waves generally have two eras: the skeuomorphic era and the native era.

tweet: Side note I left out of the tweetstorm: Web 3 tech stack is basically a parallel tech stack to Web 2. The bad news is this creates onboarding friction. The good news is this makes it easy for Web 3 commerce to cut across existing Web 2 networks.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 18/ The internet started out with so much promise, but over the last decade got taken over by a handful of giant, unseemly theme parks. We can build great cities, with thriving economies, to replace them. We have the tools, and the seeds have been planted.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 17/ Economies that grow organically, bottom-up end up looking like cities. Economies owned by a single company with top-down control end up looking like theme parks. A single company can never match the creativity of a thriving ecosystem.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 16/ Economies will be composable, meaning new ones can be built on top of existing ones. Systems and services become like lego bricks, accelerating everyone‚Äôs progress. Like what another economy did? Don‚Äôt fight it. Build your own economy alongside it.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 15/ The band gets revenue from primary issuances and cuts of resale, and possibly by owning a chunk of fungible tokens, and is incentivized along with the community to make the economy as large as possible. If you have a good idea, you are welcome to contribute or build on top.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 14/ The goods that flow through the band‚Äôs economy might be social tokens, digital art, collectibles, tickets, game objects, exclusive experiences, or whatever else creators and technologists dream up (we are still early‚Äîthere will be many more great ideas).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 13/ Now take this and apply it to, say, a band who has spent years building a following but today gets only pennies from streaming services. Using tokens and NFTs, the band can upgrade their networks into an economy.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 12/ In these communities, CryptoPunks are not ‚Äújust jpegs.‚Äù They are cultural artifacts that derive value through the shared myths, memes, stories, and experiences of their surrounding communities. Punk 6526 explains it well here: https://t.co/xj8bmhO9AD

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ What might new economies built on top of existing networks look like? We can get a glimpse of the future by looking at emerging NFT communities. For example, the CryptoPunks economy flows across Discord, Twitter, Telegram, OpenSea, Larva Labs, etc.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ A true digital economy is like a real-world bazaar. Anyone can create new goods and services, and is free to trade with anyone else. People can fully express their creativity, and enjoy the economic upside of what they produce.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ When Web 2 networks allow for commerce, it is very limited, with centrally prescribed prices, products, and buyer-seller relationships. Because of user lock-in, Web 2 take rates are extremely high. I wrote more on this here: https://t.co/ToIK4MeIz9

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ Why crypto? You could theoretically have digital economies without crypto, but crypto guarantees genuine ownership of goods (NFTs) and money (tokens), thus lowering switching costs and preventing networks from playing Web 2 games like deprecating APIs and raising take rates.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ Economies (as used here) are networks with various crypto assets freely flowing through them, from any node to any other node, directed by the decentralized participants and not by the centralized network owner.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ We are now entering a new era of the internet ‚Äî Web 3 ‚Äî where we have the chance to upgrade these networks into economies, and in the process build systems where the incentives of the network owners, network participants, and third-party developers are fully aligned.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ This is not due to bad people or motives. It‚Äôs the logic of the model. If you don‚Äôt do these things, your competitors will, and you‚Äôll be out of business. I wrote more about this here https://t.co/zumGHfZZe4

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ For example, social media companies that control large networks routinely kill off promising 3rd-party developers, fight cross-network interoperability, charge excessively high take rates, and adopt intrusive advertising models.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ These platforms gave many people an audience who didn‚Äôt previously have one. But due to fundamental structural misalignments between the networks and the companies that own them, we‚Äôve seen increasing tension around these networks‚Äô rules and economics.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 2/ We spent the last 20 years building networks on the internet. Social media platforms like Instagram, Twitter, YouTube, and Discord are networks, which can be divided into billions of smaller networks, consisting of followers, friends, subscribers, backers, etc.

name: cdixon.eth

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 18/ This is what working at the start of the S-curve feels like. Programmable blockchains are the computing frontier, as PCs were in the 80s, internet in the 90s, and mobile in the last decade.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 17/ If you work in crypto, you are used to outsiders looking at you funny or thinking what you are doing is silly or a scam. We often don‚Äôt have names for what people are working on. It‚Äôs too new.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 16/ These are some ideas, but entrepreneurs are better at building the future than people like me are at predicting it. It‚Äôs very likely the best ideas either haven‚Äôt yet been conceived or seem strange to us today.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 15/ Crypto-enabled 3D worlds and metaverse experiences let people socialize, earn money, and build mini-worlds, while guaranteeing interoperability and genuine ownership.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 14/ Blockchain-based social networks make strong commitments to users and developers, so they can build on solid ground, without worrying about changing APIs and economics.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 13/ Social tokens are new ways for creators to make money online. They remove rent-seeking intermediaries and enable the development of mini-economies that grow along with the fan base.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ What will be the next wave of blockchain killer apps? Computing waves are hard to predict, but there are some interesting emerging categories.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ To some people, NFTs seem frivolous and toy-like. But NFTs are important because they offer radically better economics to creators and developers versus existing Web 2 platforms. https://t.co/ToIK4MeIz9

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ This year NFTs and gaming were the next wave of blockchain apps to break out: NBA Top Shot, CryptoPunks, Axie Infinity, etc. You can see this reflected in the rapid growth of gross sales at OpenSea, the largest NFT marketplace: https://t.co/Phy7wKeRyl

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ DeFi shows it‚Äôs possible to build financial services that are inclusive, fair, transparent, and composable. On Wall Street, value flows inward to institutions at the center. In DeFi, value flows outward to people at the edges. https://t.co/Nyb2C7diWn

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ We saw this start to play out last year during "DeFi summer" as the first wave of crypto/blockchain killer apps broke out: Uniswap, Aave, Compound, Maker, etc.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ Programmable blockchains are interesting for the same reason mobile phones became interesting when they opened up development to 3rd parties via app stores. The best ideas tend to come from the fringes.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ We say blockchains are programmable when they have highly expressive, near Turing-complete programming languages. The most popular programmable blockchain is Ethereum.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ Blockchains are virtual computers that run on top of networks of physical computers. They have new properties and new capabilities that prior kinds of computers didn‚Äôt have. https://t.co/7SB4843Wam

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
3/ Mobile has since moved up the technology adoption S-curve. Great mobile apps will still be built, but the low-hanging fruit has been picked.

The computing frontier of this decade is building apps on programmable blockchains like Ethereum.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 2/ If you were an ambitious, risk-seeking founder in the mobile golden age circa 2009-12, you built a new mobile app. That was when Uber, WhatsApp, Instagram, Venmo, Snapchat, and many other top apps were built.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 13/ Web 2 platforms depend entirely on creators for content, yet give only scraps back. This is not sustainable. Web 2‚Äôs take rate is Web 3‚Äôs opportunity.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 12/ In contrast, Web 3 social platforms like Rally, Mirror, and BitClout have effective take rates well below 10%. Most of the value is sent back to users and creators.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ Social media platforms like Twitter, Instagram, and TikTok have take rates of 100% ‚Äî they don‚Äôt share any revenue at all with creators! That‚Äôs been great for them but bad for users.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ With NFTs, musicians keep over 90% of sales. By cutting out layers of intermediaries, musicians can credibly support themselves with just a thousand true fans: https://t.co/Z1jiraxxOB

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ Today there are over 8 million musicians on streaming services, yet less than 15,000 musicians (less that 0.2%) make more than $50K/year. That‚Äôs because the vast majority of the revenue is kept by the streaming services and music labels.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ In most video games, some people pay to get ahead and other people work to get ahead. The difference in Web 3 is that the economy is peer to peer: players fund other players, not just the game developers.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
7/ Web 3 (aka crypto) games reduce the take rate dramatically. For example, Axie Infinity has generated over $1B in gross sales in the past year,  most of which has gone back to users. 
https://t.co/4x1UNCCVMS

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ The video games industry does about $120B/year in sales, a significant portion of which is virtual goods. Most video games have 100% take rates.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ Today this trend continues as Web 3 startups begin to eat into the margins of Web 2 incumbents. The higher the take rate, the more vulnerable the incumbent.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ Craigslist did this with classifieds, Google and Facebook did this with media, TripAdvisor and Airbnb did this with travel, and so on.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ What Amazon did in commerce is what the internet did more generally. Lowering prices and redistributing value back to users has been the internet‚Äôs core economic dynamic since the 90s.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 2/ Jeff Bezos famously said "your margin is my opportunity" referring to the way Amazon took market share by lowering prices and eating into competitor margins.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 12/ The Web was a momentous invention, but, as Sep Kamvar said, if you asked people in 1989 what they needed to make their life better, it was unlikely that they would have said a decentralized network of information nodes that are linked using hypertext. https://t.co/PyKLPLWPCA

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ Steve Jobs called the computer a bicycle for the mind. As the bicycle amplifies the efficiency of our locomotion, the computer amplifies our intelligence and creativity. https://t.co/M7xMNPSM3p

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ Early on, personal computers were used mainly by enthusiasts to make games and hack around. They seemed like overpriced toys. But later, some of those early enthusiasts developed the word processor, the spreadsheet, the web browser, etc.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
9/ ‚ÄúWhat problem does it solve?‚Äù üõ†

Many breakthrough technologies, especially those involving computers, don‚Äôt directly solve problems. Instead, they unlock new capabilities, which in turn enable users, developers, creators to solve problems.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ Sequencing a human genome went from costing $100 million twenty years ago to under $1,000 today, making it broadly accessible. As Larry Page said: ‚ÄúHardware prices eventually approach the cost of the commodity material inputs.‚Äù https://t.co/q4U0y0UvRk

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ In addition to getting cheaper, hardware gets better. A modern iPhone has over 12 billion transistors, roughly 3500 times more than a 1995 Pentium PC. Today over 80% of adults worldwide have internet-connected supercomputers, aka smartphones, in their pockets. https://t.co/f9uD3fHjkU

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ Social media was a technology for creating global media networks that arrived disguised as a way to share what you had for lunch.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ When the telephone was first invented, incumbents like Western Union dismissed it, as the sound quality was poor and it only worked at short distances. They failed to imagine how quickly those things would be improved.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
2/ ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs just a toy.‚Äù üöÇ

This was the mistake made early on about breakthrough technologies like the telephone, personal computers, and social media. https://t.co/zTgz0SPN7p

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 17/ Creators can now choose to route around institutions that have been holding them back, embracing the forward progression of technology ‚Äî as video games did‚Äî instead of fighting it ‚Äî as the music industry did.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 16/ There is nothing magical about video games that makes them more monetizable than other forms of media. People love video games, but people also love music, books, films, podcasts, and digital art.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 15/ A filmmaker or writer can sell NFTs to crowdfund their creations instead of pitching traditional financing sources. Recently, a novelist raised $50K this way https://t.co/LCbDu7Eb8c and a documentary film raised $2M https://t.co/HzTKmq4LpJ

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 14/ A musician can now choose to give away new music to maximize distribution and charge for scarce complementary NFTs like digital album art, behind-the-scenes passes, and proof of fandom. The musician 3LAU made $11.6M with a recent NFT drop. https://t.co/gMfFgJ3v6S

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 13/ Even if publishers and studios, along with web 2 incumbents, resist the new model, individual creators can route around them, going direct to their fans.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 12/ NFTs are an important recent example of the internet routing around broken business models. Like open source, NFTs are a grassroots movement, led by creators extending the video game virtual goods model to their own fields.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ A classic example is open source vs proprietary software in the 90s/00s. Proprietary software vendors stuck to dated, closed source models despite strong opposition. Grassroots open source communities routed around them with entirely new software stacks.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet:
10/ Now to the main topic. The internet pioneer John Gilmore famously said that the internet treats censorship as a defect and routes around it. 

The internet does the same thing to bad business models.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ Think about that: virtual goods barely existed a decade or so ago. Now they are the primary source of revenue for the most successful products in the fastest growing media category.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 8/ Today the most sophisticated games -- Fortnite, League of Legends, Clash Royale -- give away the game itself and charge for virtual goods.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ Game makers looked at their product expansively, as a bundle that included software, services, and add-ons, and then ran experiments to discover the optimal balance between free features that maximized viral marketing and paid features that maximized revenue.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ Meanwhile, the video game industry discovered something radical: if they made the thing they previously charged for ‚Äî the game itself, the sole source of revenue for the industry ‚Äî entirely free, they could make even more money.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ The music industry responded by spending decades filing lawsuits against innovators, and eventually accepting the incremental improvement of allowing users to subscribe to bundled content via streaming platforms.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ When the internet came along, video games responded by embracing new genres like MMOs and battle royale, new business models like free-to-play and virtual goods, and new complementary behaviors like streaming.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ For a long time, video games and music had the same, straightforward business model: charge money for a perpetual license to the base content ‚Äî the game or music itself.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 2/ Let‚Äôs start with this fascinating chart (from https://t.co/z5cyM2z4jt) which raises the question: why has the video game industry grown alongside new technologies, while the music industry has not? https://t.co/mMDePxzXoo

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 1/ Topic: The internet treats bad business models as defects and routes around them. üßµüëá

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 11/ Long term, we think NFTs will onboard hundreds of millions of new users into crypto, and will be a cornerstone of Web 3, helping to free users and creators from intrusive, high take-rate centralized intermediaries.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 10/ It‚Äôs likely that NFTs will be cyclical, similar to crypto more broadly. These cycles appear chaotic but have an underlying logic as we outline here https://t.co/ZlfrLP6FX2

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 9/ The most exciting chart is the number of new developers/creative projects entering the space. Each new project expands the design space and seeds a new wave of creators and developers https://t.co/RPm7i6aI8g https://t.co/BQjP2NScOm

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 7/ The incumbent Web 2 model for funding creative people - ads and algorithmic feeds - is deeply broken. Inspired by the success of digital goods in video games, NFTs offer a much better way to make money online. I wrote more about this here https://t.co/III9SMCHXv

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 6/ ...collectibles (Top Shot), digital art (Foundation, SuperRare), and various up-and-coming new areas.

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 5/ The media narrative around NFTs has tended to focus on high priced one-off sales like Christie‚Äôs auctions, but in reality NFTs are best understood as a grassroots movement spanning a range of categories, including avatars (CryptoPunks, BAYC), games (Axie, Zed),...

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 4/ This is in stark contrast to incumbent Web 2 platforms that take anywhere from 30% (app stores) to 100% (social networks).

name: cdixon.eth
tweet: 3/ NFTs platforms generally have low take rates, ranging from 2.5% to 15% (blockchains shift power to users -> low switching costs -> low take rates). This means most of the $2.5B went to creators and collectors.
